3.2. The RNA-binding domain of nonstructural protein 1 of influenza A virus
This protein was solved at 1.9 AÀö resolution (Liu et al., 1997) as a single conformation with isotropic B factors (PDB code 1ail). The Rfree values of our three models are 0.1‚Äì0.6% higher than those of the SAR PDB structure (Table 2). The B factors of the SAR PDB structure and the three models listed in Table 2 are almost identical (see Fig. 5a), with a correlation coefÔ¨Åcient of $0.99 among them.

All three models in Table 2 as well as the reÔ¨Åned PDB structure have very similar stereochemical quality, as seen from their r.m.s.d. in bond lengths and bond angles, ‚Äô/ compatibility with the Ramachandran plot and the number of unfavorable contacts (Table 2). All the models have no residues in disallowed regions of the Ramachandran plot and can be considered as equivalent solutions for the content of the protein crystal.
The alternative conformations exhibited little variance from the PDB structure or among themselves (Fig. 6). Thus, the allatom r.m.s.d. of the new models from the SAR PDB structure is 0.19‚Äì0.68 AÀö (Table 2), which is almost two times lower than

